  "prompt": "How did Gods of Egypt get greenlit? What's the backstory of how the movie got made?",
  "response": "\"Gods of Egypt\" was a project developed by Lionsgate and directed by Alex Proyas, known for films like \"The Crow\" and \"I, Robot.\" The film was greenlit primarily due to the perceived potential for a big-budget mythological action-adventure film following the success of movies like \"300\" and the trend of epic fantasy films.\n\nThe movie had a reported budget of around $140 million and was intended to be a large-scale spectacle featuring mythological Egyptian characters. However, the film was widely criticized for its casting, with white actors playing Egyptian roles, which led to significant controversy before its release.\n\nThe project was conceived by Alex Proyas and screenwriter Matt Sazama, who wanted to create a visually spectacular reimagining of Egyptian mythology. Gerard Butler was cast as the god Set, and the film aimed to be a big-budget action-adventure with extensive CGI and elaborate visual effects.\n\nDespite the backing of Lionsgate and the involvement of established actors like Butler and Nikolaj Coster-Waldau, the film was a critical and commercial failure upon its release in 2016, receiving extremely negative reviews and performing poorly at the box office.\n\nUnfortunately, without access to specific insider information, I can only provide this general overview of the film's development based on publicly available information.",
